===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|screw|lang=enm}}, {{term|scrue||screw|lang=enm}}; apparently, despite the difference in meaning, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|escroue||nut, cylindrical socket, screwhole|lang=fro}}, of uncertain origin. There is also the {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|escruve||screw|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|odt|en}} {{term/t|odt|*scrūva}} {{gloss|"screw"; whence {{etyl|dum|-}} {{term|schruyve||screw|lang=dum}}}}, which probably influenced or conflated with the aforementioned resulting in the Middle English word.
{{rel-top|more on the etymology of ''screw''}}
Old French {{term|escroue|lang=fro}} (whence {{etyl|ML.|-}} {{term|scrofa||nut, screwhole|lang=la}}), is believed to be an adaptation of {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|scrōfa||sow, female pig|lang=la}};<ref>''Merriam-Webster's Collegiate Dictionary'', 11th edn., s.v. "screw".</ref> but this development is not found in other Romance languages.<ref>''A new English dictionary on historical principles, Vol. 8, "screw"</ref> (For change in meaning, compare also Spanish {{term|puerca|lang=es}}, Portuguese {{term|porca|lang=pt}}, both ‘sow; screw nut’, and is based on the fact that a [[boar]]'s penis has a screw-like tip, making the sow's [[vulva]] equivalent to a screw nut by [[analogy]]).

Old Dutch {{term/t|odt|*scrūva}} derives from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*skrūbō||screw}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*skru-||to cut}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*(s)keru-}}, {{term/t|ine-pro|*(s)ker-||to cut}}, and is related to {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Schraube||screw|lang=de}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|schruve|lang=nds}}, {{term|schruwe||screw|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|schroef||screw|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|skroef||screw|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|skrue||screw|lang=da}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|skruf||screw, peg|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|skrúfa||screw|lang=is}}.

Compare also Occitan {{term|escrofa||screw nut|lang=oc}}, Calabrese {{term|scrufina||screw nut|lang=it}}, which may be borrowings of the Old French word, or parallel developments. <!--Are these natural developments from a Latin ancestor term, or are they merely borrowing the French word or usage??? -->
